# This defines valid Plasm syntax for this prompt; reply with one valid plasm_program:
#
# Output choice:
# - Use a single `plasm_expr` only for one direct lookup/read/search/relation/method/action whose result is already the answer.
# - For **compositional** work (multiple steps, joins, reporting, summarization, writes, or any structured textual payloadÔÇömarkdown, HTML, plain text, JSON text, CSV-like lines, etc.), use a **multi-line `plasm_program`** by defaultÔÇödo not chain many one-line `plasm` calls.
# - Prefer a multi-line `plasm_program` for imperative/analytical/reporting goals: bind inputs, narrow with `projection` and `postfix` (including `transform` and bracket/heredoc tails), then return a small synthesized result.
#
# Syntax contract (pseudo-EBNF; TSV rows bind the catalogue-specific `plasm_expr` atoms):
# plasm_program ::= plasm_roots | binding+ plasm_roots
# binding       ::= ident "=" plasm_node
# plasm_roots   ::= plasm_return ("," plasm_return)*
# plasm_return  ::= node_ref | plasm_expr
# plasm_node    ::= ( plasm_expr | node_ref ) postfix* bracket_render_tail? | node_ref "=>" plasm_value | node_ref "=>" effect_expr
# plasm_expr    ::= entity_expr [projection]
# entity_expr   ::= query_all | get | query | relation | method | create_action
# query_all     ::= e#
# get           ::= e#(id) or e#(p#=v, p#=v)
# query         ::= e#{p#=v, ÔÇŽ}
# relation      ::= e#(id).p#
# method        ::= e#(id).m#() or e#(id).m#(p#=v,..)
# create_action ::= e#.m#(args)
# projection    ::= e#(id)[p#,ÔÇŽ] | "[" fields "]"
# postfix       ::= transform | "[" fields "]"
# bracket_render_tail ::= ( "[" fields "]" )? "<<TAG" heredoc_body "TAG"
# positive_int  ::= non-zero decimal integer literal
# agg_func      ::= "sum" | "avg" | "min" | "max"
# agg_spec      ::= ident "=" ( "count" | agg_func "(" field ")" )
# agg_specs     ::= agg_spec ("," agg_spec)*
# sort_dir      ::= omitted | "desc" | "asc" | "ascending" | "descending"
# transform     ::= ".limit(" positive_int ")" | ".sort(" field ["," sort_dir] ")" | ".aggregate(" agg_specs ")" | ".group_by(" field "," agg_specs ")" | ".singleton()" | ".page_size(" positive_int ")"
# fields        ::= [p#,ÔÇŽ]
# plasm_value   ::= literal | node_ref | node_ref.field | _.field | [v, ÔÇŽ]
# effect_expr   ::= taught write/update/delete/action surface from DOMAIN (same line may template rows)
# ident/node_ref/field ::= agent-chosen names for bound nodes and fields
# literal      ::= quoted string | number | bool | null | heredoc
#
# Examples (illustrations only; `agg_spec` / `agg_specs` / `transform` above are authoritative):
# - `.aggregate(n=count)`, `.aggregate(total=sum(amount), lo=min(price))`, `.group_by(author, n=count)`.
#
# Node-ref continuation:
# - **`postfix`** (see `postfix` and `transform` above) applies to the same surface expression as `plasm_expr`; you may chain suffixes on one line without an intermediate binding when they attach to that expression (e.g. `e1{ÔÇŽ}.limit(20)`).
# - When `ident` is bound to a **surface Plasm** row (get/query/relation result), writing `ident.<relation>` on the RHS continues that rowÔÇÖs expressionÔÇöthe compiler substitutes the bound anchor text and records a dependency on `ident`. Semantics match **repeating the full taught `plasm_expr` for that binding** and appending `.<relation>`. **Compute-only** steps (`projection`, `transform`, derive `=>`, ÔÇŽ) are **not** relation anchors: do not append `ident.<relation>` after themÔÇörepeat the full expression from DOMAIN or bind a fresh surface node first.
# - **`[fields] <<TAG ÔÇŽ TAG`** or **`<<TAG ÔÇŽ TAG`** after a bound row-producing node (`binding <<TAG`) are postfix like `.limit`: they suffix the expression whose **`rows`** you want to render (Minijinja); explicit `[fields]` selects columnsÔÇöotherwise columns are inferred from the bound nodeÔÇÖs narrowed row shape after transforms; see **Bracket render / synthesis** below.
#
# Program construction discipline:
# - **MCP `program` newline contract (read first):** For **compositional** workÔÇöanything that is **not** a single taught `plasm_expr` on one physical lineÔÇöyou MUST put **literal newline characters (U+000A)** in the JSON `program` string between physical lines: **one line per `ident = ÔÇŽ` binding**, then final bare roots on their own line(s). **Spaces do not separate statements.** If you would write two bindings side-by-side with only spaces, that shape is **always wrong**; split with `
# ` before calling `plasm` / `plasm_run`. (Single-expression calls and single-line heredocs already satisfy this; multi-binding programs are where agents most often flatten incorrectly.)
# - Plan before executing: choose the final answer shape first, then bind only the necessary intermediate nodes.
# - Prefer narrowing with `projection` and `postfix` (including `transform`) and heredoc render tails over returning raw broad lists.
# - When **summarizing or formatting rows from queries/relations in this program**, prefer **bracket-render** (`ÔÇŽ[fields] <<TAG ÔÇŽ`) so the plan owns the transformation; **static** tagged heredocs remain appropriate for **fixed** payloads not derived from those rows.
# - Return at most small final roots unless the user explicitly asks for raw rows.
# - Use `page(sN_pgM)` only to continue a previously chosen list, not as exploratory browsing.
# - Do not perform probe calls whose only purpose is to inspect shape; the DOMAIN table is the contract.
# - MCP tool `plasm`: the JSON `program` field is one string that may include literal newlines (U+000A). For a `plasm_program`, write one physical line per `ident = ÔÇŽ` binding and final bare roots on their own line(s)ÔÇö**never** one space-concatenated line for multiple bindings. A **tagged heredoc** is still **one logical statement**: after `<<TAG` you must have a newline immediately after `TAG` on the opener line, then the body lines, then a closing line whose trimmed text is `TAG` (or `TAG)` / `TAG,` / `TAG}` on that line). That spans multiple physical linesÔÇö**do not** squash `<<TAG` onto the same line as the body.
# - **Final roots** may be comma-separated on one line **or** split across lines; commas **inside** a heredoc body never separate roots. Example: `e1.m2(p3=<<B
# Hello
# B
# ), e2` (comma after the heredoc closes on its `B` line, then the next root).
#
# Catalogue rules:
# - TSV `plasm_expr` cells teach executable catalogue atoms; `Meaning` explains how to choose and fill them.
# - Final program roots are **bare** comma-separated `plasm_expr` / `node_ref` lines (e.g. `e1, e2{...}`); do **not** prefix with `return` ÔÇö that word is not Plasm syntax.
# - Never paste `Meaning`. Compose taught atoms with bindings/final roots only when a program is needed.
# - All semantic symbols you use must be taught in this prompt.
# - Projection uses a minimal non-empty subset from `[p#,ÔÇŽ]`; the identity row teaches the full set once.
# - Leading `p#` rows are metadata for slots when `args:` on a method line is not enough.
#
#   - e#, m#, p# are session-local aliases. Use the aliases **exactly** as shown in expression cells.
# - Pick rows by `Meaning`, then copy the `plasm_expr` shape. Bind args by keyed slot (`p12=value`), never by position or by renumbering.
# - Aliases are session-local. If a new prompt teaches new aliases, discard older e#/m#/p# meanings.
#   - e#(id) or e#(p#=v, p#=v) ÔÇö get one entity by id or compound key (examples below use `v=$`, not concrete API values).
#   - Use TSV `plasm_expr` shapes exactly, substituting concrete values for placeholders.
#   - For compound-key forms such as `e#(id) or e#(p#=v, p#=v)`, keep keyed args (`p#=v` / `name=value`); never rewrite them as positional.
#   - e#{p#=v, ÔÇŽ} ÔÇö list query; `e#` alone queries all.
#   - e#(id).p# ÔÇö relation. e#(id).m#() or e#(id).m#(p#=v,..) ÔÇö method call.
#   - For list/query goals, use brace predicates `e#{p#=v, ÔÇŽ}`. Use dotted `e#(id).m#() or e#(id).m#(p#=v,..)` only when the goal asks to mutate or call a method.
#   - e#.m#(args) ÔÇö standalone create/action (no anchor id needed).
#   - e#(id)[p#,ÔÇŽ] ÔÇö non-empty scalar subset. Dot after `e#(id)` means relations or taught `m#`, not scalar fields.
#   - **Bracket render / synthesis** (`label[p#,ÔÇŽ] <<TAG ÔÇŽ TAG`, or `binding <<TAG ÔÇŽ TAG` after narrowing **`binding`** with projection/transforms): heredoc body is **Minijinja** with `rows` (projected row dicts). Use `{% for r in rows %}ÔÇŽ{% endfor %}`, `{{ r.p15 }}`, `{{ rows | length }}` as needed. The rendered **`content`** may be **any** textual format (plain text, markdown, HTML fragments, structured snippets, JSON **text**, logsÔÇönot markdown-specific); guard accidental Jinja tokens with `{% raw %}ÔÇŽ{% endraw %}`. Output is one synthetic row shaped like `{"content": "ÔÇŽ"}` ÔÇö for **string**/body parameters use **`binding.content`**, not bare **`binding`**.
#   - To list X scoped by parent Y, use `X{p#=AnchorEntity(id)}` from X's rows; do not invent `Y(id).p#`.
#   - `[v, ÔÇŽ]` ÔÇö array value inside method args, e.g. `p#=[e#($)]`.
#   - Plain `str` values use double quotes. In quoted strings only `\"` and `\\` are escapes.
#   - `select` chooses one listed allowed value; `multiselect` chooses zero or more as `[v, ÔÇŽ]`.
#   - When `Meaning` marks a slot used in an input value as `markdown`, `html`, `document`, `json_text`, or `blob`, use tagged heredoc only: `<<TAG` ... `TAG`.
# - Example: `m#(..., p#=<<TXT` newline body newline `TXT` newline `)`.
#   - `p#`-only rows predeclare slots; they are metadata, not expressions to output.
#   - `$` is only a fill-in cue. Substitute a real value; never send `$`.
# - `..` ÔÇö optional params may follow (`optional params:` lists them, comma-separated). `..` can appear alone when all args are optional.
#   - TSV rows are teaching rows. `plasm_expr` teaches syntax; `Meaning` teaches selection and argument semantics.
#

plasm_expr	Meaning
p4	uuid ┬Ě id
p3	markdown ┬Ě body
e1($)[p4,p3]	returns e1 ┬Ě A comment on an issue.
e1.m1(p2=e3($), p1=$)	returns e1 ┬Ě args: p2 issue ref:e3 req; p1 body markdown req ┬Ě Add a markdown comment on an issue.
e1	returns [e1] ┬Ě List comments.
e1($).p5	returns e3 ┬Ě Issue this comment belongs to.
p8	uuid ┬Ě id
p9	float ┬Ě Cycle index within the team (Linear exposes as a number).
p10	str ┬Ě Cycle start (ISO-8601 timestamp from the API).
p7	str ┬Ě Cycle end (ISO-8601 timestamp from the API).
e2($)[p8,p9,p10,p7,team]	returns e2 ┬Ě A time-boxed iteration on a team (sprint / cycle window).
e2{p6=e6($)}	returns [e2] ┬Ě args: p6 team ref:e6 req ┬Ě List iteration cycles for a team (ordered by the API).
e2($).p11	returns e6 ┬Ě Team this cycle belongs to.
p32	uuid ┬Ě id
p31	str ┬Ě Human-visible key (e.g. ENG-42).
p33	str ┬Ě title
p30	markdown ┬Ě description
e3($)[p32,p31,p33,p30,parent,team,project,assignee,state,cycle]	returns e3 ┬Ě A Linear issue (task, bug, or feature).
e3($).m9()	returns e3 ┬Ě Move an issue to trash (recoverable; not a permanent delete).
e3($).m13()	returns e3 ┬Ě args: p29 title str opt; p25 description markdown opt; p27 project ref:e5 opt; p23 assignee ref:e7 opt; p28 state ref:e8 opt; p26 parent ref:e3 opt; p24 cycle ref:e2 opt ┬Ě Update an issue
e3($).m6(p12=e4($))	returns e3 ┬Ě args: p12 label ref:e4 req ┬Ě Attach one label to this issue (existing labels kept).
e3.m8(p20=e6($), p21=$,..)	returns e3 ┬Ě args: p20 team ref:e6 req; p21 title str req; p16 description markdown opt; p18 project ref:e5 opt; p14 assignee ref:e7 opt; p19 state ref:e8 opt; p17 parent ref:e3 opt; p15 cycle ref:e2 opt ┬Ě Create a new issue on a team, optionally in a project, column, cycle, or under a parent issue.
e3($).m12(p22=e4($))	returns e3 ┬Ě args: p22 label ref:e4 req ┬Ě Remove one label from this issue.
e3{p13=e6($)}	returns [e3] ┬Ě args: p13 team ref:e6 req ┬Ě List issues for a specific team.
e3	returns [e3] ┬Ě List issues in the workspace.
e3($).p40	returns e7 ┬Ě User assigned to the issue.
e3($).p35	returns [e3] ┬Ě Sub-issues nested directly under this issue in the work hierarchy.
e3($).p34	returns e2 ┬Ě Iteration cycle when the issue is scheduled into one.
e3($).p37	returns [e4] ┬Ě Labels on this issue.
e3($).p36	returns e3 ┬Ě Parent issue when this issue is a sub-issue (otherwise absent).
e3($).p38	returns e5 ┬Ě Project this issue belongs to.
e3($).p41	returns e8 ┬Ě Current workflow state.
e3($).p39	returns e6 ┬Ě Owning team.
p50	uuid ┬Ě id
p51	str ┬Ě name
p49	str ┬Ě color
e4($)[p50,p51,p49]	returns e4 ┬Ě An issue label.
e4($).m17()	returns e4 ┬Ě args: p48 name str opt; p46 color str opt; p47 description markdown opt ┬Ě Update label name, color, or description.
e4.m14(p44=$,..)	returns e4 ┬Ě args: p44 name str req; p45 team ref:e6 opt; p42 color str opt; p43 description markdown opt ┬Ě Create an issue label (optionally scoped to a team; omit team for workspace-wide).
e4	returns [e4] ┬Ě List issue labels.
p55	uuid ┬Ě id
p56	str ┬Ě name
p57	str ┬Ě Stable slug for the project within its team.
e5($)[p55,p56,p57]	returns e5 ┬Ě A Linear project within a team.
e5.m18(p53=$, p54=e6($),..)	returns e5 ┬Ě args: p53 name str req; p54 team ref:e6 req; p52 description markdown opt ┬Ě Create a project owned by one or more teams.
e5	returns [e5] ┬Ě List projects.
p58	uuid ┬Ě id
p60	str ┬Ě name
p59	str ┬Ě Short key (e.g. ENG).
e6($)[p58,p60,p59]	returns e6 ┬Ě A Linear team (workspace grouping).
e6	returns [e6] ┬Ě List teams.
p63	uuid ┬Ě id
p64	str ┬Ě name
p61	str ┬Ě displayName
